1Ô∏è‚É£ Implicit Cursor
Q1. Write a PL/SQL block to fetch a single employee name using an implicit cursor.
Answer
plsql
Copy code
DECLARE
    v_name Employees.name%TYPE;
BEGIN
    SELECT name INTO v_name
    FROM Employees
    WHERE emp_id = 101;

    DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE('Employee Name: ' || v_name);
END;
2Ô∏è‚É£ Explicit Cursor
Q2. Declare and use an explicit cursor to fetch employee names.
Answer
plsql
Copy code
DECLARE
    CURSOR emp_cursor IS
        SELECT name FROM Employees;
    v_name Employees.name%TYPE;
BEGIN
    OPEN emp_cursor;
    LOOP
        FETCH emp_cursor INTO v_name;
        EXIT WHEN emp_cursor%NOTFOUND;
        DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE(v_name);
    END LOOP;
    CLOSE emp_cursor;
END;
3Ô∏è‚É£ Cursor FOR Loop
Q3. Use a cursor FOR loop to display all employee names.
Answer
plsql
Copy code
DECLARE
    CURSOR emp_cursor IS
        SELECT name FROM Employees;
BEGIN
    FOR emp_rec IN emp_cursor LOOP
        DBMS_OUTPUT.PUT_LINE(emp_rec.name);
    END LOOP;
END;
